{"key":"processedPost-11185682","value":{"id":11185682,"first":11179726,"last":11185737,"when":1254755119,"utime":"10/05/09 06:05 PM","content":"Soil mixes were popular 20 to 30 years ago in casing layers.&nbsp; However, you will have a higher rate of contamination then a plain peat/verm casing that has been buffered with lime, and had gypsum added.&nbsp; It all depends on the species you're wanting to grow.&nbsp; Many don't require or benefit from a casing layer.<br /><br />You 'can' pasteurize in the oven, but it will take much longer.&nbsp; Put a meat thermometer into the substrate and keep it between 140F and 160F (60C to 70C) for one hour at the center.&nbsp; Water is a much better heat transfer media than air, so it's generally faster to use hot water pasteurization.<br />RR","title":"Re: Can I heat the soil in the owen too much?"}}